To get you started on a new project that tries to understand the differences in military expenditure across different countries, you are performing a quick summary of the data while answering a number questions that the chief business analytics leader has asked you to do. Question 9: Using the data_tab data frame, calculate the total sum of the variable military_expenditure for each of the countries in the data set selecting only the years from 1994. Store the results in a new variable called Total. (2pts). Make sure you store the new data frame in a data object called Total_expenditure and display the results (#1pt). Hint: This new data object will need to have two columns.

Total_expenditure <- data_tab %>%
  filter(military_expenditure>= 1994) %>% 
  group_by(Country) %>% 
  summarise(Total= sum(military_expenditure))

Question 10: What is the proportion of the Total_expenditure of each of the countries you stored in the object Total_expenditure (in question 9) with respect of the world? To answer this question, please create a new variable called Percentage and store the new data frame under the data object Percen_expenditure. Display the resulting data frame (this data frame must contain the variables Country, Total and Percentage) (2pts) Hint: You can calculate the percentage by dividing the Total expenditure of each country by the total world expenditure and multiply by 100.

Percen_expenditure <- Total_expenditure %>% 
 mutate(Percentage= Total/sum(Total)*100);Percen_expenditure

Question 12: Use the data object Percen_expenditure, order the observations from larger to smaller according to the Percentage variable and display the results in a table (1pt). Without including the results for the World entries, which is the country with the largest expenditure (1pt)? And with the lowest (1pt)?

or_percen_expenditure <- Percen_expenditure %>%
  slice(-6) %>% 
  arrange(desc(Percentage))

The country with the highest expenditure is United States and with the lowest is Ukraine.

Question 14: Using the data_tab data object, display in a graph the trend in militar_expenditure for the World (on the x-axis display the years and on the y-axis the miliary_expenditure values for the selected entries) (6pts). Hint: You first need to select the data that corresponds to the World entries and then create the plot. Trends are displayed with a line graph.

data_world <- data_tab %>%
  filter(Country== "World")    # Complete the rest of the code lines

ggplot(data_world,mapping = aes(x= Year, y= military_expenditure))+
  geom_line()
